#* {{quote-book|author=James Scott Walker|chapter=The Small Tunnel|title=An Accurate Description of the Liverpool and Manchester Rail-way, the Tunnel, the Bridges, and Other Works throughout the Line; an Account of the Opening of the Rail-way, and the Melancholy Incident which Occurred; a Short Memoir of the Late Right Hon. W[illia]m Huskisson, and Particulars of the Funeral Procession, &c. With a Map of the Line, and a View of the Bridge over Water Street, Manchester|edition=2nd|location=Liverpool|publisher=Printed & published by J. F. Cannell, 81, [[w:Lord Street, Liverpool|Lord-Street]]|year=1830|page=20|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=niM4AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA20|oclc=39554339|passage=In front of the latter [coach-houses for railway carriages] is a handsome building, intended as offices for the clerks of the Company, coach-offices, and apartments for the reception and accomodation of passengers, who will be conveyed thither in '''omnibusses''' from Liverpool, and taking their respective places in the travelling carriages, will be ''let off'' down the inclined plane of the little Tunnel, to be hooked to the locomotives in the area, on the other side of the hill.}}
#* {{RQ:WBsnt IvryGt|chapter=Prologue|page=16|passage=Athelstan Arundel walked home all the way, foaming and raging. No '''omnibus''', cab, or conveyance ever built could contain a young man in such a rage. His mother lived at Pembridge Square, which is four good measured miles from Lincoln's Inn.}}
#* {{quote-book|author=E[dward] M[organ] Forster|authorlink=Edward Morgan Forster|chapter={{w|The Celestial Omnibus}}. [Chapter II.]|title=The Celestial Omnibus: And Other Stories|location=London|publisher={{w|Sidgwick & Jackson}}|year=1911|oclc=222065657|location2=London|publisher2=Sidgwick & Jackson Ltd. Adam Street, [[w:Adelphi, London|Adelphi]], W.C.|year2=1912|page2=61|pageurl2=https://archive.org/stream/cu31924013613306#page/n72/mode/1up/|oclc2=23715818|passage="Please," his voice quavered through the foul brown air, "Please, is that an '''omnibus'''?" / "'''Omnibus''' est," said the driver, without turning round.}}
#* {{quote-book|author=Virginia Woolf|authorlink=Virginia Woolf|chapter=XIII|title={{w|Night and Day}}|location=London|publisher=[[w:Duckworth Overlook|Duckworth and Company]]|date=20 October 1919|oclc=934871138|location2=New York, N.Y.|publisher2=[[w:Harcourt (publisher)|Harcourt, Brace and Company]]|year2=1920|page2=160|pageurl2=https://archive.org/stream/nightday00wool#page/160/mode/1up/|oclc2=492270719|passage=When he came back to his work after lunch he carried in his head a picture of the Strand, scatted with '''omnibuses''', and of the purple shapes of leaves pressed flat upon the gravel, as if his eyes had always been bent upon the ground.}}
